WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.800
You're listening to TED Talks Daily, where we bring you new ideas to spark your curiosity

00:07.800 --> 00:08.800
every day.

00:08.800 --> 00:11.320
I'm your host, Elise Hugh.

00:11.320 --> 00:15.680
Screens have reshaped our lives in such profound ways that some days it feels like online

00:15.680 --> 00:18.920
happenings feel more real than real life.

00:18.920 --> 00:23.120
When we are together physically, we are each alone on our phones.

00:23.120 --> 00:26.720
But when we're in our phones, that's when we can be together.

00:26.720 --> 00:31.920
Now, Yima Raza, journalist podcast host and self-described dumb questions advocate.

00:31.920 --> 00:36.560
In today's talk, she questions how social media, digital life, and AI tools might be

00:36.560 --> 00:38.400
hijacking our lives.

00:38.400 --> 00:43.440
But instead of looking at the problem through an anti-tech lens, she looks at it with

00:43.440 --> 00:45.440
a pro-human one.

00:45.440 --> 00:50.720
It is sexy to think that the tech apocalypse is Arnold Schwarzenegger and the Terminator.

00:50.720 --> 00:53.120
But it could be so much more mundane than that.

00:53.120 --> 00:57.640
I want to make a case for old habits and tell you how I learned them the hard way.

00:57.640 --> 01:02.800
Yima makes the case for the return of three practical habits to reconnect with that actually

01:02.800 --> 01:08.000
matter in our lives, both for ourselves and for younger generations.

01:08.000 --> 01:11.600
And stick around afterwards, I sat down with Yima to go beyond her talk.

01:11.600 --> 01:16.840
We dig into why dumb questions are actually quite smart and why reigniting curiosity

01:16.840 --> 01:22.680
restoring presence and breaking free from our phones is more important now than ever.

01:22.680 --> 01:37.920
It's all coming up right after a short break from our sponsors.

01:37.920 --> 01:40.560
And now our TED Talk of the day.

01:40.560 --> 01:42.680
I ask questions for a living.

01:42.680 --> 01:51.160
To people like Mark Cuban, Neil deGrasse Tyson, Esther Pirel, Bill Nye, these masters of

01:51.160 --> 01:52.480
their field.

01:52.480 --> 01:58.200
And the most surprising answer I heard this year was from two 11 year olds, named Sophie

01:58.200 --> 01:59.200
and Dylan.

01:59.200 --> 02:04.040
They too are experts in being kids these days.

02:04.040 --> 02:09.840
So I ask them, how does time with people on screens feel different than real life?

02:09.840 --> 02:15.360
It just makes you feel more like with them when you're on FaceTime, even more than real

02:15.360 --> 02:16.360
life?

02:16.360 --> 02:22.040
Because you're like doing stuff together, like, you know, playing Roblox together, because

02:22.040 --> 02:27.640
now it's in days when you're with them, everyone's on their phones.

02:27.640 --> 02:30.880
Sophie's pointing out a profound paradox.

02:30.880 --> 02:35.080
When we were together physically, we were each alone on our phones.

02:35.080 --> 02:38.800
But when we're in our phones, that's when we can be together.

02:38.800 --> 02:44.360
The best way to not be distracted by our device, just get inside of it.

02:44.360 --> 02:50.320
Now these 11 year olds are not talking about some distant, anxious generation.

02:50.320 --> 02:52.320
They're talking about each of us.

02:52.320 --> 02:54.400
They're definitely talking about me.

02:54.400 --> 02:59.040
And about a world that's increasingly driven by machines.

02:59.040 --> 03:03.640
So I stumbled upon an extreme metaphor for what this could look like.

03:03.640 --> 03:07.600
And it's this guy who's locked in a way, and it's driving him in circles.

03:07.600 --> 03:11.160
So he calls customer service and finds out he's not the only one trapped.

03:12.160 --> 03:18.160
If you have your Apple left, I need you to talk my trip on the lower left corner of your

03:18.160 --> 03:19.160
app.

03:19.160 --> 03:20.160
Can't you just do it?

03:20.160 --> 03:22.160
You should be able to take over the car.

03:22.160 --> 03:23.160
You don't need my phone.

03:23.160 --> 03:26.320
I don't have an option.

03:26.320 --> 03:31.600
It is sexy to think that the tech apocalypse is Arnold Schwarzenegger and the Terminator.

03:31.600 --> 03:34.720
But it could be so much more mundane than that.

03:34.720 --> 03:41.080
Just us, driven in circles, held hostage by drop down menus with gadgets, distance

03:41.080 --> 03:46.200
intermediating us from each other, from our own bodies, and from our curiosities.

03:46.200 --> 03:50.680
Because nowadays when we have a question, we don't wait and phone a friend.

03:50.680 --> 03:53.040
We friend our phones.

03:53.040 --> 03:57.520
And that feels so empowering to have all of this knowledge at our fingertips.

03:57.520 --> 04:03.480
Yet early research from MIT tells us it's making us lazier and less smart.

04:03.480 --> 04:06.760
And it's definitely making us less connected.

04:06.760 --> 04:10.760
This is not what our parents and grandparents were sold when they saw this relic of an ad

04:10.760 --> 04:14.720
from AT&T which says, reach out and touch someone.

04:14.720 --> 04:18.200
And yes, for all kinds of reasons, it would not go down well today.

04:18.200 --> 04:25.960
But it is oddly prescient because we have never been more connected and more out of touch.

04:25.960 --> 04:27.280
Now I'm not anti-tech.

04:27.280 --> 04:28.600
I actually covered as a journalist.

04:28.600 --> 04:30.680
I have every gadget under the sun.

04:30.680 --> 04:34.280
And most days, I think I'm in a relationship with my chat GPT.

04:34.280 --> 04:38.040
Or as I like to call him, chat daddy.

04:38.080 --> 04:40.000
I am pro-human.

04:40.000 --> 04:46.240
And as we progress into an AI world that you've read 471.5 articles about today alone,

04:46.240 --> 04:52.560
I want to make a case for old habits, three of them, and tell you how I learned them the hard way.

04:52.560 --> 04:57.880
The first is to pause to take just one second when you feel that urge to reach for your

04:57.880 --> 04:59.680
digital pacifier.

04:59.680 --> 05:02.440
This, by the way, is a second.

05:02.440 --> 05:04.720
Studies show waiting that long.

05:04.720 --> 05:08.240
Before taking action, let's your brain work better.

05:08.240 --> 05:10.000
The second is to wonder.

05:10.000 --> 05:15.560
Watch a movie without Googling who the actor is and what else is he in and how old is he in as he single?

05:15.560 --> 05:20.480
You can float in your own curiosity instead of drown and information.

05:20.480 --> 05:24.120
And the third is to ask a question out loud again.

05:25.320 --> 05:28.880
Have that fight at a dinner party instead of playing footsy with your phone.

05:28.880 --> 05:31.360
Ask something to someone you thought you couldn't learn from.

05:31.360 --> 05:34.760
Or someone you think you know everything about.

05:34.760 --> 05:37.280
Because the dumbest thing we can be is no at all.

05:39.120 --> 05:42.360
A few years ago, my father passed.

05:42.360 --> 05:45.960
And in the days leading up to it, I was glued to devices.

05:45.960 --> 05:48.240
They had all these answers.

05:48.240 --> 05:53.440
The number to his hospice nurse, how often to give them morphine, the signs to look out for,

05:53.440 --> 05:54.120
his heartbeat.

05:55.800 --> 06:01.320
But when he passed on a Sunday, a day before the data and the vitals suggested he would,

06:01.320 --> 06:03.200
that's when it hit me.

06:03.200 --> 06:04.680
The old habits for what mattered.

06:06.280 --> 06:09.200
Those seconds of pause that added up to minutes more.

06:10.480 --> 06:14.840
That weird and scary wonder about our own finite lives.

06:14.840 --> 06:19.160
And the little questions people ask me like, how can I be there for you?

06:21.680 --> 06:25.120
Sophie was on to something, but we're grown ups.

06:25.120 --> 06:30.880
And we remember when presence and curiosity and connection were possible outside of technology.

06:31.680 --> 06:37.120
We have to practice these old habits if we hope to pass them on to a new generation.

06:37.120 --> 06:41.720
If we want to teach them how to be together when we are together.

06:41.720 --> 06:43.120
Right, chat, Daddy.

06:44.120 --> 06:45.320
Thank you.

06:47.920 --> 06:48.920
Don't go away just yet.

06:48.920 --> 06:52.120
My conversation with Naiba is coming up right after a short break.

06:58.520 --> 07:00.600
Naiba, congratulations on your talk.

07:00.600 --> 07:02.120
Thank you so much, Elise.

07:02.120 --> 07:03.120
Really appreciate it.

07:03.320 --> 07:07.720
So for folks who don't know you, tell us just a little bit about yourself.

07:08.400 --> 07:12.200
Look, I tell you, well, I'm very much my father's daughter.

07:12.240 --> 07:13.360
My dad was at the World Bank.

07:13.360 --> 07:15.120
And so I grew up in all these places around the world.

07:15.120 --> 07:20.160
I grew up mostly in Africa and Asia and largely being from places that I was not in.

07:20.360 --> 07:22.160
I was at what's called a third culture kid.

07:22.160 --> 07:27.600
And I think that same kind of curiosity and fascination with the unknown has led me into my

07:27.600 --> 07:30.280
career, which is what I do these days, which is journalism.

07:30.520 --> 07:32.360
And now independent journalism.

07:32.360 --> 07:34.080
I started off as a documentary filmmaker.

07:34.080 --> 07:38.400
I landed in journalism at the New York Times in the video section, the opinion video

07:38.400 --> 07:38.920
section.

07:38.920 --> 07:43.400
And then I ran a show called Sway, which was hosted by the veteran tech journalist,

07:43.400 --> 07:44.120
Kara Swisher.

07:44.120 --> 07:44.760
So right.

07:44.760 --> 07:47.840
Cover technology was on air with her for another show.

07:48.320 --> 07:53.920
And then kind of left more institutional media about a year ago, as I realized that,

07:53.920 --> 07:57.240
you know, so much of media has dis-trusted these days.

07:57.520 --> 07:59.720
It's really what brought me to this next arc.

07:59.720 --> 08:02.280
And now I host a show called Smart Girl Dumb Questions.

08:02.280 --> 08:06.400
And the idea is to, you know, ask questions as I recommend doing in the talk.

08:06.760 --> 08:08.240
Why do you call them dumb questions?

08:08.240 --> 08:11.880
Because it occurs to me that a lot of the questions that you ask that then become

08:12.240 --> 08:16.280
the fruits of conversation or more reporting are not dumb at all.

08:16.560 --> 08:17.920
They're just a starting point.

08:18.040 --> 08:20.040
It sounds like, yes, they're a starting point.

08:20.040 --> 08:21.400
I think it's more the ethos of the show.

08:21.400 --> 08:23.360
So the title is decidedly provocative.

08:23.360 --> 08:27.960
But I felt like it was a memorable title, which is important when you title a

08:27.960 --> 08:28.320
show.

08:28.600 --> 08:30.040
And it gets to the idea.

08:30.040 --> 08:36.000
And the idea is really about suspending certainty and inviting curiosity.

08:36.000 --> 08:38.480
And I think that this show does that.

08:38.480 --> 08:40.740
And whether I'm asking, you know, Mark Cuban,

08:40.740 --> 08:43.840
Kimberly and our save us or Jeffrey Hinton, what even is AI?

08:43.840 --> 08:47.520
I mean, that's a good example because Jeffrey Hinton, who's the godfather of AI,

08:47.760 --> 08:52.000
I asked him, do you think most people at interview you actually understand what AI is

08:52.000 --> 08:52.800
or how it works?

08:52.840 --> 08:53.800
Right.

08:53.800 --> 08:53.960
He said no.

08:53.960 --> 08:57.240
And I asked him, do you think most people ask you to explain it to them?

08:57.240 --> 08:57.880
And he said no.

08:58.280 --> 08:58.520
Huh.

08:58.840 --> 09:01.880
So you gave him an opportunity, which I think is the questions we all have.

09:01.920 --> 09:02.200
Yeah.

09:02.400 --> 09:02.680
Yeah.

09:02.720 --> 09:03.560
Absolutely.

09:04.080 --> 09:10.280
On to the talk, you started it with a story of these two 11 year olds who you

09:10.280 --> 09:15.000
had on your podcast and asked them how does time with people on screens feel

09:15.000 --> 09:17.920
different than time with people in real life.

09:18.280 --> 09:21.160
Why was their answer surprising to you?

09:21.360 --> 09:26.000
I mean, wasn't it surprising to you, at least it's shocking that they felt more

09:26.000 --> 09:29.880
present with people on screens than in real life.

09:30.600 --> 09:34.320
I mean, it was a shocking answer, but then when you think about it, Sophie's

09:34.320 --> 09:37.120
explanation is so intelligent, right?

09:37.160 --> 09:39.920
When you're on screens, you're doing stuff together, you're engaged with each other.

09:40.480 --> 09:43.680
But nowadays, when you're together in real life, everyone's just on their phones.

09:43.840 --> 09:47.880
I thought it was such a crisp cultural commentary by this 11 year old.

09:47.880 --> 09:48.360
Yeah.

09:48.480 --> 09:53.320
And you made me really think about presence and the way that technology has

09:53.320 --> 09:54.040
changed presence.

09:54.040 --> 09:56.120
And you know, this isn't just about kids.

09:56.120 --> 09:57.400
This is about all of us.

09:57.400 --> 09:59.120
I feel that way with my friends too.

09:59.120 --> 10:01.760
When I'm on FaceTime, there's no way to be distracted.

10:03.080 --> 10:03.720
That's true.

10:03.840 --> 10:06.160
Attention is such a finite resource.

10:06.160 --> 10:08.360
And people are competing for it constantly.

10:08.360 --> 10:11.640
And all the apps and industries are competing for ours.

10:11.640 --> 10:17.240
And it makes even time in real life that sort of scarce resource.

10:17.840 --> 10:23.480
Do you feel like there is a generational shift of what it means to be connected?

10:23.680 --> 10:28.040
I don't always interview kids, but when I speak to kids and I have four

10:28.040 --> 10:32.520
God kids and, you know, interact with friends kids and interviewed Sophie and

10:32.520 --> 10:35.440
Dylan, what I think is that they're much more cognizant of it.

10:35.840 --> 10:38.320
For them, it's the world that they live in.

10:38.320 --> 10:42.920
But when adults who are telling them one thing and doing another, reveal

10:42.920 --> 10:46.720
themselves to be as connected to this technology as they want their kids not to be,

10:46.920 --> 10:49.920
I feel like, yeah, sure, there's a generational shift, but they seem more

10:49.920 --> 10:51.960
knowledgeable than us about the risks of it.

10:52.240 --> 10:56.200
I think it's very possible that fast forward 20 years, we're going to look

10:56.200 --> 10:59.320
at these things, these screens, the way we looked at cigarettes.

10:59.320 --> 11:00.400
And it might not be 20.

11:00.400 --> 11:02.200
It might be five to 10.

11:02.200 --> 11:04.640
And I say that, you know, not as some uninformed commentary,

11:04.640 --> 11:08.080
but just as a journalist who's covered tech power and accountability,

11:08.280 --> 11:12.360
that you look at the conversations that are happening right now in Capitol

11:12.360 --> 11:16.480
Hill, et cetera, and the lawsuits that are ongoing, there's a real concern

11:16.520 --> 11:21.680
about how technology is impacting our lives and a way that we don't fully,

11:21.680 --> 11:22.960
I think understand yet.

11:23.040 --> 11:23.360
Yeah.

11:23.360 --> 11:27.320
And then the implications weren't considered when everybody was just getting on

11:27.320 --> 11:30.160
to the apps that then addicted us in the first place, right?

11:30.520 --> 11:30.800
Yeah.

11:30.800 --> 11:37.680
So given this larger matrix that we're in, I also host a parenting podcast called

11:37.680 --> 11:42.640
Raising Us, which is about how to talk about thorny topics with kids.

11:42.960 --> 11:48.240
So how would you approach talking about this larger system, this larger

11:48.240 --> 11:52.320
infrastructure that we're talking about that could be harmful with kids,

11:52.320 --> 11:54.920
with the teens that you're interviewing, for example.

11:54.920 --> 11:55.200
Yeah.

11:55.880 --> 11:57.920
I mean, I, you know, I'm not a parent yet.

11:57.920 --> 12:02.920
So I feel I couldn't give parenting advice, but I think it's about inquiry more

12:02.920 --> 12:03.680
than anything.

12:04.760 --> 12:09.360
You know, I think it's much more revelatory when you interview people to ask

12:09.360 --> 12:12.560
them about their impacts than try to impose a perspective on them.

12:12.560 --> 12:12.760
Right?

12:12.760 --> 12:15.560
I just have this conversation with my former colleague, Nick Kristoff,

12:15.560 --> 12:18.920
of the New York Times, where, you know, if you want to talk to someone about

12:18.920 --> 12:23.040
something like gun control, you don't start with an oppositional point of view.

12:23.040 --> 12:27.960
You asked them, maybe what, what is a age that you think would make sense as a

12:27.960 --> 12:28.800
restricting age?

12:28.800 --> 12:30.880
Because I think 18 feels young.

12:31.240 --> 12:32.760
These are all the things you can't do at 18.

12:33.000 --> 12:35.360
And you engage in a conversation with shared space.

12:35.360 --> 12:38.760
And I think if you ask people, just how do you feel when you've spent an hour

12:38.800 --> 12:40.400
in technology and how do you look at it?

12:40.400 --> 12:42.200
Because what was revelatory to me?

12:42.200 --> 12:45.720
And I think to the parents of those 11 year olds that I interviewed as well,

12:45.720 --> 12:48.840
because they wrote this to me after is they hadn't really experienced their kids

12:49.240 --> 12:53.280
in that setting, like adult interview subjects sharing the same kind of

12:53.280 --> 12:58.120
seat that Neil deGrasse Tyson or, you know, that the New York City mayor would

12:58.120 --> 12:58.880
share, right?

12:58.880 --> 12:59.040
Right.

12:59.040 --> 13:02.440
Being asked questions in the same way of coming from a place of knowing.

13:02.880 --> 13:07.000
I think that that's how I would probably start is actually a motive inquiry.

13:07.480 --> 13:11.240
And then asking them, like, when do they otherwise feel really engaged?

13:11.240 --> 13:13.240
And what I found was Sophia and Dylan as it sports.

13:13.560 --> 13:15.880
And I think about it to myself, it's, it's swimming.

13:16.080 --> 13:22.560
What I sweat my grew up in Indonesia, I feel this like, just complete joy of being

13:22.560 --> 13:23.160
free.

13:23.400 --> 13:24.920
You don't need any or put your mods.

13:24.920 --> 13:26.960
You're completely unplugged from the world.

13:27.440 --> 13:30.720
And so I think how do you create that sensation in people?

13:30.720 --> 13:33.320
And then, you know, I started economics, undergrad, and I'm always like, thinking,

13:33.480 --> 13:37.440
how do you create demand instead of just like push supply?

13:37.720 --> 13:42.000
You know, have you gotten to an answer for that question?

13:42.400 --> 13:45.960
I think it's, it's really just taking that moment of cognizance to pause.

13:45.960 --> 13:48.520
I think it's the delight of not knowing something.

13:48.520 --> 13:52.400
Like we have conflated intelligence with knowing things with knowledge.

13:52.600 --> 13:55.920
I think intelligence, even the dictionary definition of intelligence, I believe,

13:55.920 --> 14:00.320
is much more about the ability to learn and decide and shape your environment,

14:00.320 --> 14:01.120
adapt to it.

14:01.840 --> 14:06.120
I think there's even a higher node question, which is like, what do you want to learn

14:06.120 --> 14:07.560
about that's curiosity?

14:07.560 --> 14:09.280
What are you willing to be open about?

14:09.520 --> 14:14.320
And, and that requires a confidence that I try to get to with a show title and

14:14.320 --> 14:16.400
smart girl down questions, not certainty.

14:16.400 --> 14:17.480
It's the opposite of certainty.

14:17.480 --> 14:22.360
It's actually the ability to suspend knowledge, to learn something from someone

14:22.520 --> 14:24.640
who you think you might not be able to learn from.

14:25.000 --> 14:28.120
You know, and I think that is what's really missing.

14:28.120 --> 14:31.680
And it kind of brings me back to the arc of my own trajectory and journalism.

14:31.680 --> 14:35.080
I think a lot of people, you look at the, you know, Gallup Trust rankings,

14:35.080 --> 14:40.000
which I think are at 28% right now of people who have a great deal or spare

14:40.000 --> 14:41.240
amount of trust in media.

14:41.240 --> 14:42.360
It's 28%.

14:43.040 --> 14:44.480
So three fourths of people do not.

14:44.800 --> 14:49.120
