that the asking questions, like the, the interrogative part of journalism has faded

14:55.760 --> 15:00.120
away and kind of been taken over by opinion journalism or hot takes or, you know,

15:00.120 --> 15:01.720
influencers are telling you what to think.

15:01.720 --> 15:03.800
And I think most people are like, I know how to think.

15:03.800 --> 15:05.880
I've just like you to help me get information.

15:06.000 --> 15:06.200
Yeah.

15:06.960 --> 15:13.000
And then what do you think is the connection between inquiry, being curious, wonder

15:13.280 --> 15:17.520
and rebuilding trust or just maintaining connections with one another?

15:18.160 --> 15:20.160
I think you can't do one without the other, right?

15:20.160 --> 15:21.720
At least like connections and trust.

15:21.800 --> 15:23.400
They go hand in hand in a way.

15:23.920 --> 15:28.320
I think the act of curiosity and the act of being willing to be wrong or to not

15:28.320 --> 15:31.680
know or to learn creates like a physical space that I feel.

15:31.960 --> 15:34.560
Oh, there's something between us that we can fill.

15:34.720 --> 15:36.200
We can learn together, right?

15:36.200 --> 15:41.040
And I think curiosity is like at the heart of that, not for play, not for

15:41.040 --> 15:43.840
show, but you're genuinely actually curious about something.

15:44.000 --> 15:46.280
And by the way, you could say, look, there are certain things I know.

15:46.280 --> 15:49.240
The sky is blue, the, you know, the floor is down, whatever it is.

15:49.640 --> 15:53.360
But I guarantee you there is something you can learn from somebody else.

15:53.360 --> 15:57.240
And if you ask a person a question, there are two things that happen, I think.

15:57.440 --> 16:01.360
One is you disarm that person to want to share something with you.

16:01.600 --> 16:04.560
The second is actually there's studies from, I think it was the University

16:04.560 --> 16:05.440
of California systems.

16:05.440 --> 16:07.040
I think it was a decade ago in 2014.

16:07.280 --> 16:10.840
They did some studies where they showed that when you're in a curiosity mindset,

16:11.040 --> 16:14.160
you're actually able to learn more and not just learn about the thing you're

16:14.160 --> 16:17.640
asking about or curious about, but learn all kinds of adjacencies.

16:17.880 --> 16:22.000
So you kind of build that plasticity and retain the ability to learn and who

16:22.000 --> 16:23.320
doesn't want to do that, right?

16:23.320 --> 16:26.600
So I think you changed the other, you changed yourself and you changed the space

16:26.600 --> 16:27.160
between you.

16:27.360 --> 16:27.960
I love that.

16:28.480 --> 16:33.400
Why do you think then if curiosity and asking questions can be so

16:33.400 --> 16:38.680
